==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fulka-'' ‘warlike, army’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[folk]], Old Saxon ''folc'' (Dutch [[volk]]), Old High German ''folc'' (German [[Volk]]), Old Norse [[folk]] ‘people, army’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /folk/

===Noun===
'''folc''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''folc''')
# a [[people]], a [[nation]], a [[race]]
# an [[army]]
# ''(in plural)'' people in general

